# Engineering Standards

## TypeScript

- `strict: true` always. No `any` — use precise types, generics, or `unknown` with
  narrowing.
- JSON columns are typed at the boundary with Zod schemas; never consume untyped JSON.
- Zod schemas are the single source of validation, shared between React Hook Form
  resolvers and API route handlers.

## Production-Ready Only

- No temporary hacks, no `// TODO: fix later` shortcuts, no commented-out code.
- Handle the failure paths that can actually happen (external providers, file uploads,
  job failures) — surface them as typed API errors, not silent catches.
- Every API response uses the `{ data }` / `{ error: { code, message } }` envelope.

## Structure

- Feature-based folders (`src/features/*`); services own business logic
  (`src/server/services`); see `architecture.mdc` for layering.
- No duplicated business logic — extract to the service or `src/lib`.
- One Prisma model per concept; no parallel data shapes.

## Components

- Reuse `src/components/ui` primitives (see `design-system.mdc`).
- Server Components by default; `"use client"` only where interactivity requires it.
- Data fetching via React Query hooks in `src/features/*/hooks`; mutations invalidate
  affected queries.

## Testing-Ready Patterns

- Services are pure functions of (context, input) → result; they receive the org
  context as an argument and are independently testable.
- Providers are injected behind interfaces — tests can substitute fakes without
  network access.
- Keep route handlers thin enough that service tests cover the real logic.
